'''''Verbascum thapsus''''' ('''great mullein''' or '''common mullein''') is a species of [[Verbascum|mullein]] native to Europe, northern Africa, and Asia, and introduced in the Americas and Australia. 

It is a hairy [[biennial plant]] that can grow to {{convert|2|m}} tall or more. Its small yellow flowers are densely grouped on a tall stem, which grows from a large [[Rosette (botany)|rosette]] of leaves. It grows in a wide variety of habitats, but prefers well-lit disturbed soils, where it can appear soon after the ground receives light, from long-lived seeds that persist in the [[soil seed bank]]. It is a common weedy plant that spreads by prolifically producing seeds, but it rarely becomes aggressively [[invasive species|invasive]], since its seeds require open ground to [[germination|germinate]]. It is a very minor problem for most agricultural crops, since it is not a very competitive species, being intolerant of shade from other plants and unable to survive [[Tillage|tilling]]. It also hosts many insects, some of which can be harmful to other plants. Although individuals are easy to remove by hand, populations are difficult to eliminate permanently.

It is widely used for herbal remedies, with well-established [[emollient]] and [[astringent]] properties. Mullein remedies are especially recommended for coughs and related problems, but also used in [[topical]] applications against a variety of skin problems. The plant has also been used to make [[dye]]s and [[torch]]es.

== Description ==

[[Image:Starr 040723-0260 Verbascum thapsus.jpg|left|thumb|alt=|A stemless rosette in [[Hawaii]]]]

''Verbascum thapsus'' is a [[dicotyledon]]ous plant that produces a [[rosette (botany)|rosette]] of leaves in its first year of growth.<ref name="FlEu">{{cite encyclopedia | last = Ferguson | first = Ian Keith | editor = Tutin, Thomas Gaskell et al. | encyclopedia = [[Flora Europaea]] | title = V.&nbsp;thapsus | year = 1972 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | volume = Volume 3: Diapensiaceae to Myoporaceae | location = Cambridge | page = 211 | isbn = 0-521-08489-X}}</ref><ref name="blamey">Blamey, M., & Grey-Wilson, C. (1989). ''Flora of Britain and Northern Europe''. Hodder & Stoughton, ISBN 0-340-40170-2.</ref> The leaves are large, up to 50&nbsp;cm long. The second year plants normally produce a single unbranched stem, usually 1<U+2013>2&nbsp;m tall. In the eastern part of its range in China, it is, however, only reported to grow up to 1.5&nbsp;m tall.<ref name="china">{{Cite web|title=Verbascum thapsus|url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=2&taxon_id=200021301|work=Flora of China|publisher=eFloras.org|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> The tall pole-like stems end in a dense [[raceme|spike]] of flowers<ref name="FlEu"/> that can occupy up to half the stem length. All parts of the plants are covered with star-shaped [[trichome]]s.<ref name="china"/><ref name="jepson">{{cite web|last=Wetherwax|first=M.| year=1993|title=Verbascum thapsus L. |url=http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/cgi-bin/get_JM_treatment.pl?7177,7595,7598 |work=Jepson Manual online|publisher=[[University of California at Berkeley]]|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> This cover is particularly thick on the leaves, giving them a silvery appearance. The species' [[chromosome number]] is 2n&nbsp;=&nbsp;36.<ref name="NWeurope"/>

On flowering plants the leaves are alternately arranged up the stem. They are thick and [[decurrent]], with much variation in leaf shape between the upper and lower leaves on the stem, ranging from [[leaf shape|oblong to oblanceolate]], and reaching sizes up to 50&nbsp;cm long and 14&nbsp;cm across (19&nbsp;inches long and 5&nbsp;inches wide).<ref name="huxley">Huxley, A., ed. (1992). ''New RHS Dictionary of Gardening''. Macmillan. ISBN 0-333-47494-5</ref><ref name="remaley"/> They become smaller higher up the stem,<ref name="FlEu"/><ref name="blamey"/> and less strongly decurrent down the stem.<ref name="FlEu"/> The flowering stem is solid and 2<U+2013>2.5&nbsp;cm (nearly an inch) across, and occasionally [[branch]]ed just below the [[inflorescence]],<ref name="blamey"/> usually following damage.<ref name="Hoshovsky">{{cite web|first=Marc C.|last= Hoshovsky|title=Element Stewardship Abstract for Verbascum thapsus|url=http://www.invasive.org/weedcd/pdfs/tncweeds/verbtha.pdf|format=PDF|date=August 2001 |publisher= The Global Invasive Species Initiative|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> After flowering and seed release the stem and fruits usually persist in winter,<ref name="illinois"/> drying into dark brown, stiff structures of densely packed, ovoid-shaped and dry seed capsules. The dried stems may persist into the following spring or even the next summer. The plant produces a shallow [[taproot]].<ref name="remaley"/>

[[Image:Starr 040723-0267 Verbascum thapsus.jpg|upright|thumb|alt=|A closeup of the flowers]]
Flowers are pentamerous with (usually) five [[stamen]], a 5-lobed [[calyx tube]] and a 5-petalled [[Corolla (flower)|corolla]], the latter bright yellow and an 1.5<U+2013>3&nbsp;cm (0.5<U+2013>1&nbsp;inch) wide. The flowers are almost [[Sessility (botany)|sessile]], with very short [[pedicel (botany)|pedicels]] (2&nbsp;mm, 0.08&nbsp;in). The five stamens are of two types, with the three upper stamens being shorter, their filaments covered by yellow or whitish hairs, and having smaller [[anther]]s, while the lower two stamens have [[glabrous]] filaments and larger anthers.<ref name="jepson"/><ref group="note">They are all hairy in subspecies ''crassifolium'' and ''giganteum''.</ref> The plant produces small ovoid (6&nbsp;mm, 0.24&nbsp;in) [[capsule (fruit)|capsules]] that split open by way of two valves, each capsule containing large numbers of minute brown [[seed]]s less than a millimetre (0.04&nbsp;in)<ref name="davis"/> in size, marked with longitudinal ridges. A white-flowered form, ''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' f. ''candicans'', is known to occur.<ref name="pennel"/> Flowering lasts for up to three months from early to late summer (June to August in northern Europe),<ref name="blamey"/> with flowering starting at the bottom of the spike and progressing irregularly upward; each flower opens for part of a day and only a few open at the same time around the stem.<ref name="illinois"/>

== Taxonomy ==
For the purpose of [[botanical nomenclature]], ''Verbascum thapsus'' was first described by [[Carolus Linnaeus]] in his 1753 ''{{lang|la|[[Species Plantarum]]}}''. The [[specific name (botany)|specific epithet]] ''thapsus'' had been first used by [[Theophrastus]] (as {{lang|el|[[:wikt:<U+0398><U+03AC><U+03C8><U+03BF><U+03C2>|<U+0398><U+03AC><U+03C8><U+03BF><U+03C2>]]}}, ''{{lang|el|Thapsos}}'')<ref name="carnoy"/> for an unspecified herb from the [[Ancient Greece|Ancient Greek]] settlement of Thapsos, near modern [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], [[Sicily]],<ref name="carnoy">{{fr icon}}{{cite book| last=Carnoy| first=A. |title=Dictionnaire <U+00E9>tymologique des noms grecs de plantes| year=1959|location=Louvain| publisher= Publications Universitaires| oclc=3284108}}</ref><ref>{{sv icon}} [http://linnaeus.nrm.se/flora/di/scrophularia/verba/verbtha.html Den virtuella Floran: ''Verbascum thapsus''], retrieved on November 6, 2009.</ref> though it is often assimilated to the ancient [[Tunisia]]n city of [[Thapsus]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Charters|first=Michael L.|title=Plant name: T| work= California Plant Names: Latin and Greek Meanings and Derivations| url=http://www.calflora.net/botanicalnames/pageT.html#thapsus|publisher=Calflora.net| accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref>

At the time, no [[type specimen]] was specified, as the practice only arose later, in the 19th century. When a lectotype (type selected amongst original material) was designated, it was assigned to specimen 242.1 of Linnaeus' herbarium, the only ''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' specimen.{{#tag:ref|The lectotypification is usually attributed to Arthur Huber-Morath (1971) ''Denkschriften der Schweizerischen Naturforschenden Gesellschaft''  87:43. Some disagree since Huber-Morath did not specifically cite sheet 242.1, and credit instead L. H. Cramer, in Dassanayake & Fosberg (1981) ''A Revised Handbook to the Flora of Ceylon'' 3:389.<ref name="florida-atlas">{{Cite web| title=''Verbascum thapsus'': citation| url=http://www.florida.plantatlas.usf.edu/Plant.aspx?id=1757| work=Atlas of Florida vascular Plants | publisher=Institute for Systematic Botany |accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref>|group=note}} The species had previously been designated as [[type species]] for ''[[Verbascum]]''.<ref>{{cite web| title=''Verbascum thapsus''| url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/jdsml/research-curation/projects/linnaean-typification/detail.dsml?ID=925400| work=Linnaean Plant Name Typification Project| publisher=Natural History Museum| accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> European plants exhibit considerable [[phenotype|phenotypical]] variation,<ref name="BoCW"/> which has led to the plant acquiring many [[synonymy|synonyms]] over the years.<ref name="florida-atlas"/><ref>{{Cite web| title=''Verbascum thapsus'' synonymy| url=http://www.northernontarioflora.ca/chklst.cfm?speciesid=1004482| publisher=Northern Ontario Plant Database|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> Introduced American populations show much less variation.<ref name="BoCW"/>

The taxonomy of ''Verbascum'' has not undergone any significant revision since Svanve M<U+00FC>rbeck's monographies in the 1930s, with the exception of the work of Arthur Huber-Morath, who used informal group in organizing the genus for the floras of Iran and Turkey to account for many intermediate species. Since Huber-Morath's groups are not taxonomical, M<U+00FC>rbeck's treatment is the most current one available, as no study has yet sought to apply genetic or molecular data extensively to the genus. In M<U+00FC>rbeck's classification, ''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' is placed in section ''Bothrospermae'' subsect. ''Fasciculata'' (or sect. ''Verbascum'' subsect. ''Verbascum'' depending on nomenclatural choices) alongside species such as ''[[Verbascum nigrum]]'' (black or dark mullein), ''[[Verbascum lychnitis]]'' (white mullein) and ''[[Verbascum sinuatum]]'' (wavy-leaved mullein).<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Farideh |last1=Attar |first2=Atefeh |last2=Keshvari |first3=Ahmad |last3=Ghahreman |first4=Shahin |last4=Zarre |first5=Fatemeh |last5=Aghabeigi |display-authors=1 |year=2007 |title=Micromorphological studies on Verbascum (Scrophulariaceae) in Iran with emphasis on seed surface, capsule ornamentation and trichomes |journal=Flora <U+2013> Morphology, Distribution, Functional Ecology of Plants |volume=202 |issue=2 |pages=169<U+2013>175 |doi=10.1016/j.flora.2006.04.001}}</ref><ref name="iberica"/>

=== Subspecies and hybrids ===

There are three usually recognized [[subspecies]]:
* ''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' subsp. ''thapsus''; type, widespread.
* ''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' subsp. ''crassifolium'' (Lam.) Murb.; Mediterranean region and to 2000 metres in southwestern Austria.<ref name=schmeil/> (syn. subsp. ''montanum'' (Scrad.) Bonnier & Layens)
* ''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' subsp. ''giganteum'' (Willk.) Nyman; Spain, endemic.
In all subspecies but the type, the lower stamens are also hairy.<ref>{{ca icon}} {{cite web|title=''Verbascum thapsus'' L. subsp. ''montanum'' (Schrad.) Bonnier et layens |url=http://herbarivirtual.uib.es/cas-med/especie/4440.html| publisher=Universitat de les Illes Balears| work=Herbario Virtual del Mediterr<U+00E1>neo Occidental| accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> In subsp. ''crassifolium'', the hairiness is less dense and often absent from the upper part of the anthers, while lower leaves are hardly decurrent and have longer petioles.<ref name=schmeil>{{cite book| last =Schmeil| first =Otto|author2=Fitschen, Jost |author3=Seybold, Siegmund | title =Flora von Deutschland, 93. Auflage| publisher =Quelle & Meyer Verlag| year =2006| location =Wiebelsheim| isbn =3-494-01413-2| page =496 }}</ref> In subsp. ''giganteum'', the hairs are densely white tomentose, and lower leaves strongly decurrent. Subsp. ''crassifolium'' also differs from the type in having slightly larger flowers, which measure 15<U+2013>30&nbsp;mm wide, whereas in the type they are 12<U+2013>20&nbsp;mm in diameter.<ref name=schmeil/> Both subsp. ''giganteum'' and subsp. ''crassifolium'' were originally described as species.<ref name="FlEu"/> Due to its morphological variation, ''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' has had a great many subspecies described. A recent revision led its author to maintain ''V.&nbsp;giganteum'' but sink ''V.&nbsp;crassifolium'' into synonymy.<ref name="iberica">{{es icon}} {{cite encyclopedia |last=Bened<U+00ED> Gonzalez |first=Carles |year=2009 |title=Verbascum |url=http://www.floraiberica.org/floraiberica/texto/pdfs/13_144_01_Verbascum.pdf |encyclopedia=[[Flora Iberica]] |volume=Volumen XIII: Plantaginaceae-Scrophulariaceae |pages=49<U+2013>97 |location=Madrid |publisher=Real Jard<U+00ED>n Bot<U+00E1>nico |isbn=978-84-00-08747-0}}</ref>

