The plant is also parent to several hybrids (''see table''). Of these, the most common is ''V.''&nbsp;<U+00D7>&nbsp;''semialbum'' Chaub. (<U+00D7> ''V.&nbsp;nigrum'').<ref name="NWeurope"/> All occur in Eurasia,<ref name="NWeurope"/> and three, ''V.''&nbsp;<U+00D7>&nbsp;''kerneri'' Fritsch, ''V.''&nbsp;<U+00D7>&nbsp;''pterocaulon'' Franch. and ''V.''&nbsp;<U+00D7>&nbsp;''thapsi'' L. ([[Synonymy|syn.]] ''V.''&nbsp;<U+00D7>&nbsp;''spurium'' W.D.J.Koch), have also been reported in North America.<ref name="kartesz"/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://web.archive.org/web/20101119114746/http://plants.usda.gov/java/profile?symbol=VERBA| title=''Verbascum'' L.| work=PLANTS Profile| publisher=USDA Natural resources Conservation Service| accessdate=2007-03-07}}</ref>

=== Common names ===
''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' is known by a variety of names. European reference books call it "great mullein".<ref name="jncc">{{cite web|title=Great Mullein ''Verbascum thapsus'' Linnaeus|url=http://www.jncc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=3316&SpeciesID=26550&type=species|work=Wildlife Statistics|publisher=Joint Nature Conservation Committee|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref><ref name="grieve"/><ref name="elsevier633">[[#Watts|Watts (2000)]], pp. 633<U+2013>634.</ref> In North America, "common mullein" is used <ref>{{cite book| last=Niering |first=William A. |title=  The Audubon Society field guide to North American wildflowers, eastern region| location=New York| publisher=Knopf| year=1979| isbn=0-394-50432-1|page=798}}</ref><ref name="Rickett">{{cite encyclopedia|title=The Mulleins (Verbascum)|page=389| encyclopedia=Wild Flowers of the United States| volume=Volume 1. The Northeastern States (Part 2)| year=1966| editor=Harold William Rickett|location=New York| publisher=McGraw-Hill|lccn=66017920}}</ref> while western United States residents commonly refer to mullein as "cowboy toilet paper".<ref name="tpwmag">{{cite web|title=Beyond the River|url=http://www.tpwmagazine.com/archive/2006/jan/ed_6/|work=Texas Parks & Wildlife Magazine|publisher=Dale Weisman|accessdate=2010-06-26}}</ref><ref name="utexas">{{cite web|title=BIO 406D-Native Plants|url=http://www.sbs.utexas.edu/bio406d/packets/Fall%2005/F05-FT1-StEd.pdf|work=An Introduction to the Flora of Central Texas|publisher=Michael Gruenstaeudl|accessdate=2010-06-26}}</ref>

In the 19th century it had well over 40 different common names in English alone. Some of the more whimsical ones included "hig candlewick", "indian rag weed", "bullicks lungwort", "Adams-rod", "hare's-beard" and "ice-leaf".<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia| last=Britton| first=Nathaniel A.|author2=Addison Brown | encyclopedia=An illustrated flora of the northern United States and Canada |volume=V.&nbsp;3. Gentianaceae to Compositae| year=1979| publisher=Dover Publications |location=New York| page=175| isbn=0-486-22644-1}}</ref> Vernacular names include innumerable references to the plant's hairiness: "woolly mullein", "velvet mullein" or "blanket mullein",<ref name="elsevier633"/><ref>{{cite book| last=Brako| first=Lois| coauthors=Amy Y. Rossman and David F. Farr| title=  Scientific and common names of 7,000 vascular plants in the United States| year=1995|location=  St. Paul, Minnesota| publisher=APS Press| isbn=0-89054-171-X| page=189}}</ref> "beggar's blanket", "Moses' blanket", "poor man's blanket", "Our Lady's blanket" or "old man's blanket",<ref name="grieve"/><ref name="Rickett"/><ref>[[#Watts|Watts (2000)]], pp. 108, 369.</ref> and "feltwort", and so on ("flannel" is another common generic name).

Some names refer to the plant's size and shape: "shepherd's club(s)" or "staff", "[[Aaron's Rod]]" (a name it shares with a number of other plants with tall, yellow inflorescences), and a plethora of other "X's staff" and "X's rod".<ref name="grieve"/><ref name="Rickett"/><ref>[[#Watts|Watts (2000)]], pp. 774<U+2013>775, 819<U+2013>820. p. 866: "A tall plant like Mullein attracts 'staff' and 'rod' names."</ref> The name "velvet dock" or "mullein dock" is also recorded, where "dock" is a British name applied to any broad-leaved plant.<ref>[[#Watts|Watts (2000)]], pp. 302, 634.</ref>

== Distribution and habitat ==

''Verbascum thapsus'' has a wide native range including [[Europe]], northern [[Africa]] and [[Asia]], from the [[Azores]] and [[Canary Islands]] east to western [[China]], north to the [[British Isles]], [[Scandinavia]] and [[Siberia]], and south to the [[Himalayas]].<ref name="china"/><ref name="flora">[http://rbg-web2.rbge.org.uk/cgi-bin/nph-readbtree.pl/feout?FAMILY_XREF=&GENUS_XREF=Verbascum&SPECIES_XREF=thapsus Flora Europaea: ''Verbascum thapsus''], retrieved on November 6, 2009.</ref><ref name="grin">[http://www.ars-grin.gov/cgi-bin/npgs/html/taxon.pl?41150 Germplasm Resources Information Network: ''Verbascum thapsus''], retrieved on November 6, 2009.</ref> In northern Europe, it grows from sea level up to 1,850&nbsp;m altitude,<ref name="blamey"/> while in China it grows at 1,400<U+2013>3,200&nbsp;m altitude.<ref name="china"/>

It has been introduced throughout the temperate world, and is [[naturalisation (biology)|established]] as a [[weed]] in [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], tropical Asia, [[La R<U+00E9>union]], [[North America]], [[Hawaii]], [[Chile]], [[Hispaniola]] and [[Argentina]].<ref name = "grin"/><ref>{{Es icon}} {{cite web|title=  Ficha de la Especie ''Verbascum thapsus''|url=http://www.uns.edu.ar/inbiar/ver_especie.asp?especie_id=333|work=Base de Datos sobre Invasiones Biol<U+00F3>gicas en Argentina|publisher=Universidad Nacional del Sur|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref><ref name="ISSG">{{cite web|title=''Verbascum thapsus''|url=http://www.issg.org/database/species/ecology.asp?si=695|date=8 July 2005|work=Global Invasive Species Database|publisher=IUCN Invasive Species Specialist Group|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= ''Verbascum thapsus'' |url=http://www.hear.org/Pier/species/verbascum_thapsus.htm| publisher= Hawaiian Ecosystems at Risk project |work= Pacific Island Ecosystems at Risk| date=February 19, 2007|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> It has also been reported in [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite web| title=List of alien species recognized to be established in Japan or found in the Japanese wild (as of October 27, 2004)| url=http://www.env.go.jp/en/nature/as/041110.pdf|format=PDF| accessdate=2009-11-06| work=Japan Ministry of Environment}}</ref>

In the United States it was imported very early in the 18th{{#tag:ref|The 1630 number in Mitch may be a typo: the beginning of the 18th century is cited in other sources.<ref name="remaley" /><ref name="BoCW" />|group=note}} century and cultivated for its medicinal and [[piscicide]] property. By 1818, it had begun spreading so much that [[Amos Eaton]] thought it was a native plant.{{#tag:ref|Eaton went so far as to write: "When botanists are so infatuated with wild speculation, as to tell us the mullein was introduced, they give our youngest pupils occasion to sneer at their teachers."<ref name="pennel">{{Cite book| last=Pennel| first=Francis Whittier| title=The Scrophulariaceae of eastern temperate North America| year=1935| publisher=George W. Carpenter Fund| location=Philadelphia| pages=173<U+2013>174| oclc=852625}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="remaley"/><ref name="mitch">{{cite web|last=Mitch|first=Larry W.|title=  Common Mullein<U+2014>the Roadside Torch Parade|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20090702071108/http://wssa.net/Weeds/ID/WorldOfWeeds/mullein.html |work=Intriguing World of Weeds|publisher=Weed Science Society of America|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> In 1839 it was already reported in [[Michigan]] and in 1876, in [[California]].<ref name="remaley">{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Remaley|title=Verbascum thapsus|url=http://www.nps.gov/plants/alien/fact/veth1.htm|year=1998|publisher=Plant Conservation Alliance's Alien Plant Working Group|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> It is now found commonly in all the states.<ref>{{cite web|title=Verbascum thapsus|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20101016082110/http://plants.usda.gov/java/profile?symbol=VETH| work=PLANTS Database| publisher=[[United States Department of Agriculture|USDA]] [[Natural Resources Conservation Service]]| accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> In [[Canada]], it is most common in the [[Maritime Provinces]] as well as southern [[Quebec]], [[Ontario]] and [[British Columbia]], with scattered populations in between.<ref name="BoCW"/><ref>{{cite web|title=''Verbascum thapsus''|url=http://www.natureserve.org/explorer/servlet/NatureServe?searchName=verbascum+thapsus|work=NatureServe Explorer|accessdate=2009-11-06}}[]: , retrieved December 29, 2006.</ref>

Great mullein most frequently grows as a colonist of bare and disturbed soil, usually on sandy or chalky ones.<ref name="NWeurope"/> It grows best in dry, sandy or gravelly soils, although it can grow in a variety of habitats, including banksides, meadows, roadsides, forest clearings and pastures. This ability to grow in a wide range of habitats has been linked to strong [[Phenotype#Phenotypic_variation|phenotype variation]] rather than [[adaptation]] capacities.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Parker|first=Ingrid M.|author2=Joseph Rodriguez |author3=Michael E. Loik | title=An Evolutionary Approach to Understanding the Biology of Invasions: Local Adaptation and General-Purpose Genotypes in the Weed Verbascum thapsus|journal=Conservation Biology|volume=17 |issue=1 |pages=59<U+2013>72 |date=February 2003 |doi=10.1046/j.1523-1739.2003.02019.x}}</ref>

== Ecology ==

[[Image:Starr 040723-0074 Verbascum thapsus.jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=A Mullein plant growing in aa dry, mountainous area.|''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' grows best where there is little competition.]]

Great mullein is a biennial and generally requires [[vernalization|winter dormancy]] before it can flower.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/> This dormancy is linked to [[starch]] degradation activated by low temperatures in the root, and [[gibberellin]] application bypasses this requirement.<ref name="phyt"/> Seeds germinate almost solely in bare soil, at temperatures between 10&nbsp;<U+00B0>C and 40&nbsp;<U+00B0>C.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/> While they can germinate in total darkness if proper conditions are present (tests give a 35% germination rate under ideal conditions), in the wild, they in practice only do so when exposed to light, or very close to the soil surface, which explains the plant's habitat preferences. While it can also grow in areas where some vegetation already exists, growth of the rosettes on bare soil is four to seven times more rapid.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/>

Seeds germinate in spring and summer. Those that germinate in autumn produce plants that overwinter if they are large enough, while rosettes less than 15&nbsp;cm (5.9&nbsp;in) across die in winter. After flowering the entire plant usually dies at the end of its second year,<ref name="Hoshovsky"/> but some individuals, especially in the northern parts of the range, require a longer growth period and flower in their third year. Under better growing conditions, some individuals flower in the first year.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Reinartz|first=James A.|title=Life History Variation of Common Mullein (''Verbascum Thapsus''): I. Latitudinal Differences in Population Dynamics and Timing of Reproduction |journal=The Journal of Ecology |volume=72 |issue=3 |date=November 1984 |pages=897<U+2013>912 |issn=0022-0477|doi=10.2307/2259539|jstor= 2259539}}</ref> Triennial individuals have been found to produce fewer seeds than biennial and annual ones. While year of flowering and size are linked to the environment, most other characteristics appear to be genetic.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Reinartz|first=James A.|title=Life History Variation of Common Mullein (''Verbascum Thapsus''): III. Differences Among Sequential Cohorts |journal=The Journal of Ecology |volume=72 |issue=3|date=November 1984|pages=927<U+2013>936|doi=10.2307/2259541 |jstor= 2259541}}</ref>

A given flower is open only for a single day, opening before dawn and closing in the afternoon.<ref name="BoCW"/> Flowers are [[reproduction#Autogamy|self-fecundating]] and [[Dichogamy|protogynous]] (with female parts maturing first),<ref name="BoCW"/> and will self-pollinate if they have not been [[pollination|pollinated]] by insects during the day. While many insects visit the flowers, only some bees actually accomplish pollination. ''V.&nbsp;thapsus''' flowering period lasts from June to August in most of its range, extending to September or October in warmer climates.<ref name="remaley"/><ref name="Hoshovsky"/><ref name="davis"/> Visitors include [[Halictidae|halictid]] bees and [[hoverfly|hoverflies]].<ref name="illinois">{{cite web|last=Hilty| first=John| title=Great Mullein|url=http://www.illinoiswildflowers.info/weeds/plants/great_mullein.htm|work= Weedy Wildflowers of Illinois|publisher=Illinois Wildflowers| accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> The hair on lower stamens may serve to provide footholds for visitors.<ref name="BoCW"/>

[[Image:Verbascum thapsus fruit kz.jpg|thumb|alt=A close-up of the green capsules of V.&nbsp;thapsus, surrounded by the sepals|The fruit of great mullein contains large numbers of minute seed.]]
The seeds maintain their germinative powers for decades, up to a hundred years, according to some studies.<ref name="beal">{{Cite journal|last=Kivilaan| first=A.|author2=Robert S. Bandurski | title= The One Hundred-Year Period for Dr. Beal's Seed Viability Experiment| journal=American Journal of Botany|volume=69| issue=9|date=October 1981| pages=1290<U+2013>1292| issn=0002-9122| doi= 10.2307/2443054|jstor= 2443054}}</ref> Because of this, and because the plant is an extremely prolific seed bearer (each plant produces hundreds of capsules, each containing up to 700+ seeds,<ref name="BoCW"/> with a total up to 180,000<ref name="remaley"/><ref name="Hoshovsky"/> or 240,000<ref name="davis"/> seeds), it remains in the [[soil seed bank]] for extended periods of time, and can sprout from apparently bare ground,<ref name="Hoshovsky"/> or shortly after [[forest fire]]s long after previous plants have died.<ref name="davis"/> Its population pattern typically consists of an ephemeral adult population followed by a long period of dormancy as seeds.<ref name="BoCW"/> Great mullein rarely establishes on new grounds without human intervention because its seeds do not disperse very far. [[biological dispersal|Seed dispersion]] requires the stem to be moved by wind or animal movement; 75% of the seeds fall within 1 m of the parent plant, and 93% fall within 5 m.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/>

[[Megachilidae|Megachilid]] bees of the genus ''[[Anthidium]]'' use the hair (amongst that of various woolly plants) in making their [[nest]]s.<ref>{{cite book |first=Paul |last=Westrich |year=1996 |chapter=Habitat requirements of central European bees and the problems of partial habitats|chapterurl= http://www.paul-westrich.de/downloads/westrich_40.pdf |editor=Matheson & al. (eds.) |title=The Conservation of Bees |series=Linnean Society Symposium Series, '''18''' |pages=1<U+2013>16 |location=London |publisher=Academic Press}}</ref> The seeds are generally too small for birds to feed on,<ref name="illinois"/> although the [[American Goldfinch]] has been reported to consume them.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Coutlee| first=Ellen L.| title=Maintenance Behavior of the American Goldfinch| url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v075n04/p0342-p0357.pdf|format=PDF| journal=Wilson Bulletin| volume=75 |issue=4 |date=December 1963 |pages=342<U+2013>357 |issn=0043-5643}}</ref> Other bird species have been reported to consume the leaves ([[Hawaiian Goose]])<ref>Banko, Paul C., Black, Jeffrey M. and Banko, Winston E. (1999). [http://bna.birds.cornell.edu/bna/species/434/articles/introduction Hawaiian Goose (''Branta sandvicensis'')], The Birds of North America Online (A. Poole, Ed.). Ithaca: Cornell Lab of Ornithology.</ref> or flowers ([[Palila]]),<ref>Banko, Paul C. ''et al.'' (2002). [http://bna.birds.cornell.edu/bna/species/679/articles/introduction Palila (''Loxioides bailleui'')], The Birds of North America Online (A. Poole, Ed.). Ithaca: Cornell Lab of Ornitholog.</ref> or to use the plant as a source when [[foraging]] for insects ([[White-headed Woodpecker]]).<ref>Garrett, Kimball L., Raphael, Martin G. and Dixon, Rita D. (1996). [http://bna.birds.cornell.edu/bna/species/252/articles/introduction White-headed Woodpecker (''Picoides albolarvatus'')], The Birds of North America Online (A. Poole, Ed.). Ithaca: Cornell Lab of Ornithology.</ref>

== Agricultural impacts and control ==
Because it cannot compete with established plants, great mullein is no longer considered a serious agricultural weed and is easily crowded out in cultivation,<ref name="BoCW">{{Cite journal| last=Gross| first=Katherine L.|author2=Patricia A. Werner | title=The Biology of Canadian Weeds. 28. ''Verbascum thapsus'' L. and ''V.&nbsp;blattaria'' L| journal=Canadian Journal of Plant Science| volume=58| pages= 401<U+2013>413|date=April 1978| doi=10.4141/cjps78-062| issue=2}} Reprinted in Mulligan, G.A. (1979), ''The Biology of Canadian Weeds'' I, ISBN 0-662-10668-7, pp. 320<U+2013>331.</ref> except in areas where vegetation is sparse to begin with, such as [[California]]n semi-desertic areas of the Eastern [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]]. In such ecological contexts, it crowds out native herbs and grasses; its tendency to appear after [[forest fire]]s also disturbs the normal [[ecological succession]].<ref name="Hoshovsky"/><ref name="davis"/> Although not an agricultural threat, its presence can be very difficult to completely eradicate, and is especially problematic in [[overgrazing|overgrazed]] pastures.<ref name="remaley"/><ref name="Hoshovsky">Hoshovsky (2001)</ref><ref name="davis">{{Cite web|last=Pitcairn|first=Michael|title=Verbascum thapsus |url=http://www.cal-ipc.org/ip/management/ipcw/pages/detailreport.cfm@usernumber=87&surveynumber=182.php |work=Invasive Plants of California's Wildland|publisher=California Invasive Plant COuncil|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> The species is legally listed as a [[noxious weed]] in the American state of [[Colorado]] (Class C)<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado State-listed Noxious Weeds|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20090702071108/http://plants.usda.gov/java/noxious?rptType=State&statefips=08| work=PLANTS Database| publisher=USDA Natural Resources Conservation Service| accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> and Hawaii,<ref>{{cite web|title=Hawaii State-listed Noxious Weeds|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20101008175302/http://plants.usda.gov/java/noxious?rptType=State&statefips=15| work=PLANTS Database| publisher=USDA Natural Resources Conservation Service| accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> and the Australian state of [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]] (regionally prohibited in the [[West Gippsland]] region, and regionally controlled in several others).<ref>{{cite web|last=Faithful| first=Ian| title=Great Mullein| url=http://web.archive.org/web/20110315090054/http://www.dpi.vic.gov.au/dpi/nreninf.nsf/LinkView/D2FE171D9ECA1CC9CA256BCF000AD563ECC844336D72F0634A256DEA00293F8A | publisher=Victoria Department of Primary Industries |accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref>

Despite not being an agricultural weed in itself, it [[Host (biology)|hosts]] a number of insects and [[disease]]s, including both [[pest (organism)|pests]] and [[beneficial insects]].<ref name="horton">{{cite journal |last= Horton|first= David R.|author2=Tamera M. Lewis |date=December 2003|title= Numbers and types of arthropods overwintering on common mullein, Verbascum thapsus L. (Scrophulariaceae), in a central Washington fruit-growing region|journal= Journal of the Entomological Society of British Columbia|volume= 100|pages= 79<U+2013>86|issn=0071-0733|url= http://web.archive.org/web/20101016082110/http://www.sfu.ca/biology/esbc/Journal/journal2003/2003_Horton.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> It is also a potential reservoir of the [[cucumber mosaic virus]], ''[[Erysiphum cichoraceum]]'' (the cucurbit [[powdery mildew]]) and [[Texas root rot]].<ref name="BoCW"/><ref>{{cite journal| last=Price| first=W. C.| title=Comparative Host Ranges of Six Plant Viruses| journal=American Journal of Botany|date=July 1940|volume=57|issue=7|pages=530<U+2013>541|issn=00029122| doi=10.2307/2437088|jstor=2437088}}</ref> A study found ''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' hosts insects from 29 different [[family (biology)|families]]. Most of the pests found were [[western flower thrips]] (''Frankliniella occidentalis''), ''[[Lygus]]'' species such as the [[tarnished plant bug]] (''L. lineolaris''), and various spider mites from the family [[Tetranychidae]]. These make the plant a potential reservoir for [[overwintering]] pests.<ref name="horton"/>

Other insects commonly found on great mullein feed exclusively on ''Verbascum'' species in general or ''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' in particular. They include mullein thrips (''[[Haplothrips]] verbasci''),<ref name="horton"/> ''[[Gymnaetron tetrum]]'' (whose larva consume the seeds) and the [[mullein moth]] (''Cucullia verbasci'').<ref name="remaley"/> Useful insects are also hosted by great mullein, including predatory mites of the genera ''[[Galendromus]]'', ''[[Typhlodromus]]'' and ''[[Amblyseius]]'', the [[minute pirate bug]] ''Orius tristicolor''<ref name="horton"/> and the [[mullein plant bug]] (''Campylomma verbasci'').<ref>{{cite web|last=Higbee|first=Bradley S.|title=Campylomma verbasci (Meyer)|url=http://www.biocontrol.entomology.cornell.edu/predators/Campylomma.html| work=Biological Control: A Guide to Natural Enemies in North America| publisher=[[Cornell University]]|accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref> The plant's ability to host both pests and beneficials makes it potentially useful to maintain stable populations of insects used for biological control in other cultures, like ''Campylomma verbasci'' and ''Dicyphus hesperus'' ([[Miridae]]), a predator of [[whitefly|whiteflies]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ferguson |first=Gillian |date= 26 September 2005 |title=Can ''Dicyphus hesperus'' control whiteflies in greenhouse tomatoes? |url=http://web.archive.org/web/20060127011547/http://www.omafra.gov.on.ca/english/crops/facts/dicyphus.htm|publisher=Ontario Ministry of Agriculture, Food and Rural Affairs|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Sanchez|first=Juan Antonio|author2=David R. Gillespie |author3=Robert R. McGregor |title=The effects of mullein plants (''Verbascum thapsus'') on the population dynamics of ''Dicyphus hesperus'' (Heteroptera: Miridae) in tomato greenhouses|journal=Biological Control|volume=28|issue=3|date=November 2003|pages=313<U+2013>319| doi=10.1016/S1049-9644(03)00116-6}}</ref> A number of pest [[Lepidoptera]] species, including the [[Stalk Borer]] (''Papaipema nebris'') and [[Gray Hairstreak]] (''Strymon melinus''), also use ''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' as a host plant.<ref>{{cite web|title=HOSTS <U+2013> a Database of the World's Lepidopteran Hostplants|url= http://avalanche.nhm.ac.uk/jdsml/research-curation/projects/hostplants//list.dsml?searchPageURL=index.dsml&Familyqtype=starts+with&Family=&PFamilyqtype=starts+with&PFamily=&Genusqtype=starts+with&Genus=&PGenusqtype=starts+with&PGenus=verbascum&Speciesqtype=starts+with&PSpeciesqtype=starts+with&PSpecies=thapsus&sort=Family |publisher=The [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]]|accessdate=2009-11-06|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080627170707/http://avalanche.nhm.ac.uk/jdsml/research-curation/projects/hostplants//list.dsml?searchPageURL=index.dsml&Familyqtype=starts+with&Family=&PFamilyqtype=starts+with&PFamily=&Genusqtype=starts+with&Genus=&PGenusqtype=starts+with&PGenus=verbascum&Speciesqtype=starts+with&PSpeciesqtype=starts+with&PSpecies=thapsus&sort=Family |archivedate = June 27, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref>

[[Image:Starr 040723-0032 Verbascum thapsus.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=A series of leaves are seen wrapping down the length of a stem. The leaves have thick veining and both them and the stem have a woolly appearance from the hair covering them.|Because of the plant's hairiness, ''Verbascum thapsus'' is resistant to grazing and contact herbicides.]]

Control of the plant, when desired, is best managed via mechanical means, such as hand pulling and hoeing, preferably followed by sowing of native plants. Animals rarely [[grazing|graze]] it because of its irritating hairs, and liquid [[herbicide]]s require [[surfactant]]s to be effective, as the hair causes water to roll off the plant, much like the [[lotus effect]]. Burning is ineffective, as it only creates new bare areas for [[seedling]]s to occupy.<ref name="remaley"/><ref name="Hoshovsky"/><ref name="davis"/> ''G. tetrum'' and ''Cucullia verbasci'' usually have little effect on ''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' populations as a whole.<ref name="davis"/> Goats and chickens have also been proposed to control mullein.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/> Effective (when used with a surfactant) contact herbicides include [[glyphosate]],<ref name="remaley"/><ref name="davis"/> [[triclopyr]]<ref name="remaley"/> and [[sulfurometuron-methyl]].<ref name="davis"/> Ground herbicides, like [[tebuthiuron]], are also effective, but recreate bare ground and require repeated application to prevent regrowth.<ref name="Hoshovsky"/>

== Uses ==
Great mullein has been used since ancient times as a remedy for skin, throat and breathing ailments. It has long had a medicinal reputation, especially as an [[astringent]] and [[emollient]], as it contains [[mucilage]], several [[saponin]]s, [[coumarin]] and [[glycoside]]s. [[Dioscorides]] recommended it for diseases of the [[lung]] and it is now widely available in health and herbal stores. Non-medical uses have included [[dye]]ing and making [[torch]]es.

=== Medical uses ===
[[File:Verbasci flos dried.jpg|thumb|"Verbasci flos": dried flowers of ''Verbascum thapsus'' as used in herbal tea]]
[[Pedanius Dioscorides|Dioscorides]] first recommended the plant 2000 years ago, against pulmonary diseases,<ref name="silverman">{{cite book |last=Silverman |first= Maida| year=1977| title=A City Herbal: Lore, Legend, & Uses of Common Weeds| chapter=Mullein| chapterurl=http://www.ashtreepublishing.com/Book_City_Herbal_Mullen.htm |pages=99<U+2013>104|isbn= 1-888123-00-1 |publisher=Ash Tree Publishing}}</ref> and this has remained one of its primary uses, especially against [[cough]]. Leaf [[decoction]]s or [[herbal tea]]s were used for [[expectoration]], consumption, dry cough, [[bronchitis]], sore throat and [[hemorrhoid]]s. Leaves were also smoked against pulmonary ailments, a tradition that in America was rapidly transmitted to [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]]  peoples.<ref name="grieve">{{cite encyclopedia|last=Grieve|first=Margaret|encyclopedia=A Modern Herbal|title=Mullein, Great|origyear=1931|year=1982|url=http://botanical.com/botanical/mgmh/m/mulgre63.html |accessdate=2009-11-06| location=New York |publisher=Dover Publication|volume= Volume 2: I-Z|isbn=0-486-22799-5}}</ref><ref name="hanrahan">{{cite encyclopedia | last = Hanrahan | first = Claire |author2=Rebecca J. Frey  | editor = Jacqueline L. Longe | encyclopedia = The Gale encyclopedia of alternative medicine | title = Mullein | url = http://web.archive.org/web/20090715111125/http://enotes.com/alternative-medicine-encyclopedia/mullein | accessdate = 2006-11-30 | edition = 2nd | year = 2005 | publisher = Thomson Gale | volume = Volume 3: L-R | location = Detroit | isbn = 0-7876-7427-3}}</ref> The [[Zuni people]], however, use the plant in [[poultice]]s of powdered root applied to [[Ulcer (dermatology)|sore]]s, [[rash]]es and skin infections. An infusion of the root is also used to treat [[athlete's foot]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Camzine |first=Scott |first2=Robert A. |last2=Bye |year=1980 |title=A Study Of The Medical Ethnobotany Of The Zuni Indians of New Mexico |journal=Journal of Ethnopharmacology |volume=2 |issue=4 |pages=365-388;378 |doi=10.1016/S0378-8741(80)81017-8}}</ref>  The combination of [[expectorant]] saponins and emollient mucilage makes the plant particularly effective for cough. All preparations meant to be drunk have to be finely filtered to eliminate the irritating hairs.<ref name="phyt">{{Cite journal| last=Turker|first=Arzu Ucar |author2=Ekrem Gurel |title=Common Mullein (''Verbascum thapsus'' L.): Recent Advances in Research|journal=Phytotherapy Research |volume=19| issue=9|date=September 2005 |pages=733<U+2013>739|doi=10.1002/ptr.1653| pmid=16222647}}</ref>

Oil from the flowers was used against [[catarrh]]s, [[colic]]s and, in [[Germany]], [[earache]]s, [[frostbite]], [[eczema]] and other external conditions.<ref name="grieve"/> Topical application of various ''V.&nbsp;thapsus''-based preparations was recommended for the treatment of [[wart]]s,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Drury|first=Susan| title=Plants and Wart Cures in England from the Seventeenth to the Nineteenth Century: Some Examples |journal=Folklore| volume=102| issue=1| year=1991| pages=97<U+2013>100|jstor=1260360|doi=10.1080/0015587X.1991.9715809}}</ref> [[boil]]s, [[carbuncle]]s, hemorrhoids, and [[chilblain]]s, amongst others.<ref name="grieve"/><ref name="hanrahan"/> Recent studies have found that great mullein contains [[glycyrrhizin]] compounds with [[bactericide]] and potential anti-[[tumor]]al action. These compounds are concentrated in the flowers.<ref>{{cite journal| last=Turker|first=Arzu Ucar |author2=N. D. Camper | title=Biological activity of common mullein, a medicinal plant|journal= Journal of Ethnopharmacology |date=October 2002| volume=82| issue=2<U+2013>3| pages=117<U+2013>125 | doi=10.1016/S0378-8741(02)00186-1| pmid=12241986}}</ref> Different extracts have varying levels of [[efficacy]] against bacteria.{{clarify|reason=it should be specified whether this is in vitro activity or activity against actual bacterial infection in an organism, two very different types of efficacy|date=September 2014}}<ref name="phyt"/> The German [[Commission E]] sanctioned medicinal use of the plant for catarrhs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mullein flower|url=http://www.herbalgram.org/iherb/commissione/Monographs/Monograph_0262.html |work= The Commission E Monographs| date=February 1, 1990|publisher=American Botanical Council |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20060511234235/http://www.herbalgram.org/iherb/commissione/Monographs/Monograph_0262.html |archivedate=2006-05-11 |accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> It was also part of the [[National Formulary]] in the United States<ref name="hanrahan"/> and United Kingdom.<ref name="grieve"/> The plant's leaves, in addition to the seeds, have been reported to contain [[rotenone]], although quantities are unknown.<ref name="pfaf">{{cite web|title=Verbascum thapsus| url=http://www.pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Verbascum_thapsus |publisher=Plants For A Future |accessdate= 2011-03-16}}</ref>

=== Other uses ===
Like many ancient medicinal plants ([[Pliny the Elder]] describes it in his ''[[Natural History (Pliny)|Naturalis Historia]]''),{{#tag:ref|In book 25, Pliny describes "two principal kinds [of verbascum]" thought to be ''V.&nbsp;thapsus'' and ''V.&nbsp;sinuatum''. The precise attribution of a third kind is unclear.<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus:text:1999.02.0138&query=chapter%3D%232114 Latin], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus:text:1999.02.0137%3Ahead%3D%231784 English]</ref>|group=note}} great mullein was linked to [[witch]]es,<ref name="grieve"/> although the relationship remained generally ambiguous, and the plant was also widely held to ward off [[curse]]s and [[evil spirit]]s.<ref name="grieve"/><ref name="phyt"/><ref name="silverman"/><ref name="hanrahan"/> The seeds contain several compounds (saponins, glycosides, coumarin, rotenone) that are toxic to fish, and have been widely used as [[piscicide]] for [[fishing]].<ref name="remaley"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wilhelm| first=Gene| title=The mullein: Plant piscicide of the mountain folk culture| journal=[[Geographical Review]]| volume=64| issue=2| pages=235<U+2013>252|date=April 1974| doi=10.2307/213812|jstor=213812}}</ref>

The flowers provide dyes of bright yellow or green, and have been used for [[hair dye]].<ref name="grieve"/><ref name="pfaf"/> The dried leaves and hair were made into [[candle wick]]s, or put into shoes to help with insulating them. The dried stems were also dipped into [[suet]] or [[wax]] to make torches.<ref name="grieve"/><ref name="hanrahan"/> Due to its weedy capacities, the plant, unlike other species of the genus (such as ''[[Verbascum phoeniceum|V.&nbsp;phoeniceum]]''), is not often cultivated.

The stalk can also be dried as a spindle for [[making fire]] either by hand drill or [[bow drill]].

